observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require Inventory Committee to conduct physical count on 13 PPE accounts totaling ₱220.662 million;
Direct the Accounting and Property Units to reconcile their records to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in the Property Cards (PCs) and the PPELCs within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee, to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts.
Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for all obsolete or unserviceable PPEs which is to be used for dropping from the books;
Comply with the uniform property identification system and prominently show in the property sticker the PPEs vital information to include: description of the property, model number, serial number, acquisition date/cost, person accountable, space for the validation/signature of the Inventory Committee; and
Require the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain the PCs to facilitate the required regular reconciliation of the PPE accounts.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to retrieve all available records on the execution of Deed of Donations;

Request a certified true copy of the land title donated to Municipality of Maayon from Registry of Deeds;

Require Municipal Treasurer to keep track of documents relative to Properties of the Municipality; and

Come up with a proposed budget for litigation, titling and relocation and make representation with the Sangguniang Bayan to prioritize the appropriation of funds necessary to pursue the claim and transfer of Torrens Title in its name of the Municipality.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
a. Instruct the property custodian to maintain an efficient property management by following the prescribed procedures in property recording and maintain accurate and complete property records;
b. Create Inventory Committee and assign additional personnel for the inventory committee, if needed;
c. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the property custodian to adjust the books of accounts and the property records respectively, as warranted, after reconciliation; and
d. Continuously reconcile the result of the physical count with the property and accounting records.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each category of assets  and Real Property Ledger Cards for land;
Require the OIC Municipal Treasurer to maintain Property Cards for each category of assets;

Direct the Inventory/Appraisal Committee to assess the value of the assets submitted per office/.division and prepare/certify correct the corresponding RPCPPE to be approved by the Municipal Mayor;

Submit the same inventory report to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year; and

Reconciled RPCPPE with the accounting records and make necessary adjustments if there are discrepancies noted.

